{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b625fced-c114-4ba7-bf6f-15f32e5280f6","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\nHere are the main tools for .NET crash dump analysis:\n\n### `dotnet-dump analyze`\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump   # if not installed\ndotnet-dump analyze <your-file>.dmp\n```\nUseful SOS commands inside the session:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n- `pe` — print the last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap overview (for OOM crashes)\n- `threads` — list all managed threads\n- `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` — inspect other threads\n\n### `lldb` (Linux)\n```bash\nlldb --core <your-file>.dmp\nplugin load libsosplugin.so\nclrstack\npe\n```\n\n### Visual Studio (Windows)\nOpen the `.dmp` file directly — it provides a rich GUI for inspecting threads, exceptions, and memory.\n\n---\n\n**Quick triage steps:**\n1. Run `pe` to check for an unhandled exception\n2. Run `clrstack` to see where it crashed\n3. If OOM, use `dumpheap -stat` to find memory hogs\n\nWould you like me to walk you through running any of these on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d7719169-1634-4872-8743-69f3714e3d84","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\". So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":440,"requestId":"6081:14D5C9:10B34A4:151F690:69FFE576"},"id":"b537e8c4-5c2e-40d4-8912-43c642e8af57","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:55:14.313Z","parentId":"66c26aa1-d8dc-4f2b-9382-7cafae79faf7"}
